  "stages": [
    {
      "stage": "awareness",
      "description": "Adversarial Assessment (Ch 1-3): Lirien arrives in Duskhaven under a live kill contract and begins by studying Kaelith as a target, not a woman; Kaelith senses surveillance almost immediately and responds with commander-grade threat assessment. Their first recognitions are professional: Kaelith notices Lirien's operative stillness and impossible precision, while Lirien realizes the disgraced Oathbranded exile is far sharper than the file promised. Attraction registers only as heightened threat perception — heat in Kaelith's palms, disruptive target interference in Lirien's calculus. Fantasy interleave: this stage also establishes the Oathbrand anomaly, the first visible Pallor tears, and the crucial paradox seed that killing Kaelith may destroy access to the Quietus before either woman consciously understands why.",
      "targetChapters": [1, 2, 3]
    },
    {
      "stage": "attraction",
      "description": "Grudging Respect (Ch 4-6): Forced proximity begins when outside pressure collapses the option of distance. Lirien discovers enough of the Quietus paradox to delay the contract, and Kaelith chooses tactical alliance over isolation when Conclave-linked threats and the failing sky make staying in Duskhaven impossible. Respect is earned under pressure: Kaelith sees that Lirien never wastes motion or words; Lirien sees that Kaelith, even half-dead and suppressed, still reads terrain, danger, and intent better than anyone alive. The romance beat is competence-as-attraction, still resisted by both. Fantasy interleave: the journey toward the Quietus begins, hunters close in, and the conspiracy around Kaelith's maintained suppression becomes active rather than background menace.",
      "targetChapters": [4, 5, 6]
    },
    {
      "stage": "attraction",
      "description": "Unwanted Attraction (Ch 7-10): On the road, assessment turns personal. Shared watches, food-sharing across changing cultural contexts, and repeated survival under Pallor damage force each woman to notice details she would rather file elsewhere: the steadiness of Kaelith's hands even while they shake from pain, the exact way Lirien's composure fractures when Kaelith is endangered. Physical awareness intrudes before either is ready — proximity, scent, gaze, the charged restraint of not touching. Internal resistance peaks here: Kaelith's guilt-as-identity frames desire as indulgence she does not deserve, while Lirien experiences wanting Kaelith as structural failure and mission corruption. Fantasy interleave: clues about the High Conclave's sabotage accumulate, Ythara's influence makes certainty more fragile, and Lirien's need to keep Kaelith alive becomes inseparable from the world's need for the Quietus path.",
      "targetChapters": [7, 8, 9, 10]
    },
    {
      "stage": "resistance",
      "description": "Trust as Crisis (Ch 11-14): Trust stops being optional and becomes the price of survival. Lirien removes the Oathbrand — hands at Kaelith's collarbone, no emotional shield left intact — and Kaelith remains still for her in the most dangerous act of surrender she has made since Calwrath. Kaelith's magic returns in a flood; shared magical working under pursuit creates the resonance bond, which does not cause trust so much as reveal that trust has already started. Information is shared reluctantly but meaningfully: Kaelith allows Lirien to witness the truth of Calwrath, and Lirien begins to act like Kaelith's safety matters beyond strategy. First kiss belongs here because it is not a victory lap but the breaking point after accumulated restraint. Fantasy interleave: restored magic allows the Quietus path to awaken in Kaelith's body, while the bond helps them survive Pallor tears and Ythara's destabilizing influence.",
      "targetChapters": [11, 12, 13, 14]
    },
    {
      "stage": "surrender",
      "description": "Physical Intimacy as Vulnerability (Ch 14-16): The first full intimate scene is steamy, deliberate, and frightening because it is the first thing either woman does that cannot be defended as tactical necessity. Kaelith stops using her body as a site of punishment; Lirien stops using hers as an instrument of contract. Bodies become the language they can manage before clean confession: desire, care, witness, and the terrifying possibility of being chosen. This is not reward after danger — it is the thematic turning point where each risks becoming emotionally legible to the other. Fantasy interleave: the intimacy follows survival under Ythara's pressure, so physical closeness functions as coherence against unraveling; choosing touch is also choosing to remain one self in a world of dissolving possibilities.",
      "targetChapters": [14, 15, 16]
    },
    {
      "stage": "resistance",
      "description": "The Black Moment (Ch 16-18): The live contract is revealed in full — not only that Lirien was sent to execute Kaelith, but that the binding remains active, that Kaelith's blood was used in the ceremony, and that every hard-won trust moment existed inside a cage built for Kaelith's death. For Kaelith, this hits the Calwrath wound from a new angle: once again an institution used her body, her competence, and her trust for a morally compromised end, and this time the person she let closest was the mechanism. For Lirien, the revelation proves the Court's shaping went all the way down; even her love can be read as contract contamination. Kaelith walks away, and the separation feels final. Fantasy interleave: this collapse lands amid accelerating Pallor failure and direct pursuit, so the romance and the world crisis hit nadir together — if they cannot repair trust, they likely cannot reach the Quietus in time either.",
      "targetChapters": [16, 17, 18]
    },
    {
      "stage": "commitment",
      "description": "Resolution / Commitment (Ch 19-22): Recovery is earned through action rather than apology. Lirien follows Kaelith not because Court, contract, or world logic leaves her no choice, but because she has finally identified desire as her own. Kaelith does not return to trust by forgetting the betrayal; she returns by judging Lirien with full knowledge and deciding that chosen truth inside a damaged structure still counts. Together they exploit the contract loophole: Lirien stops Kaelith's heart, the binding registers fulfillment, and then Lirien restarts it. The cage opens. After that, neither woman has to stay. They still choose each other while also choosing the work of stopping Thalen's conspiracy and reaching the Quietus. The ending is HFN: love survives because it has moved from necessity to choice, and the world survives because that choice makes the final fantasy solution possible.",
      "targetChapters": [19, 20, 21, 22]
    }
  ],
  "internalResistance": {
    "leadA": {
      "fear": "Kaelith fears that loving Lirien will prove she is still the woman who can make the right tactical choice at unbearable human cost; to need anyone again is to risk becoming the blast radius of her own decisions, especially when Lirien arrives carrying the authority and instrumental logic of yet another institution.",
      "wound": "Calwrath fused guilt into identity. Kaelith's self-sufficiency, refusal to ask for help, and distrust of institutional actors are all extensions of the lie that isolation is penance rather than cowardice; if Lirien sees the full truth and stays, Kaelith loses the structure she built her self-hatred around."
    },
    "leadB": {
      "fear": "Lirien fears that attachment is structural failure, that 'home' is only the place that owns her, and that choosing Kaelith over the Court will reveal she has never made a real choice before; even worse, the contract's physiological binding makes desire feel like malfunction rather than freedom.",
      "wound": "The Cerith Court shaped Lirien into a weapon and named it belonging. She cannot instinctively distinguish obedience from loyalty or usefulness from love, so every step toward Kaelith threatens the worldview that kept her coherent through forty-three prior kills."
    }
  },
